It looks like the issue is a naming mismatch between your configuration and how Waybar handles custom modules in CSS.

In Waybar, all custom modules are assigned a CSS ID based on their name in the JSON config. Since your module is named "custom/network", Waybar looks for the ID #custom-network in your CSS. While you have #custom-network defined, there are a few common reasons why it might be failing to apply.

1. The Underscore vs. Hyphen Trap
In your CSS, you have:

CSS
#custom-network { ... }
This is generally correct, as Waybar converts the / in "custom/network" to a -. However, if your script outputs a specific class or if there's a conflict with the built-in #network ID, it can get messy.

2. Specificity and the "Bulk" Selector
You have a large block in your CSS that defines general padding and color for a long list of modules:

CSS
#clock,
#battery,
...
#network,
#custom-network,
... {
    padding: 0 10px;
    color: #ffffff;
}
Further down, you try to override it with:

CSS
#custom-network {
    background: #282828;
    color: #ebdbb2;
}
If the CSS isn't reloading properly or if another rule is taking precedence, the module might just be inheriting the #ffffff from the bulk list.

Recommended Fixes
Fix A: Use the exact Class name
Waybar also assigns a class called .custom-network (with a dot). Sometimes using the class selector is more reliable than the ID selector. Try changing your CSS block to this:

CSS
/* Target both the ID and the Class for maximum compatibility */
#custom-network, 
.modules-right > widget > #custom-network {
    background-color: #282828 !important;
    color: #ebdbb2 !important;
    padding: 0 10px;
    border-radius: 8px;
}
Fix B: Check your Script Output
Since your module is set to "return-type": "json", Waybar expects a specific JSON format. If your script get_wifi.sh isn't returning a valid "class" field, the .disconnected or .connecting styles will never trigger.

Your JSON output from the script should look like this for the CSS classes to work:

JSON
{"text": "Connected", "class": "connected"}
Fix C: Verify the "Bulk" list
Remove #custom-network from that massive list of modules at the top of your CSS. If it's included in a list that sets color: #ffffff, it might be fighting with your specific styling later on.

Pro-Tip for Debugging
Run Waybar from your terminal to see if it throws any CSS parsing errors:

Bash
killall waybar && waybar
It will output warnings if it finds a selector it doesn't recognize or if your JSON script is providing malformed data.

