Fair enough. I’ve been chasing the wrong tail. Let’s look at the one thing that actually breaks Waybar's CSS ID mapping when using custom modules: The naming convention in the JSON vs. the CSS.

In your config.jsonc, you named the module:
"custom/network"

When Waybar sees a / in a custom module name, it does not always map it to #custom-network in the CSS. It often maps it to #custom-custom-network or simply fails to generate the ID you expect because of the double "network" naming (one internal, one custom).

The Precise, No-Bulls**t Solution
Rename the module in config.jsonc to something unique that doesn't conflict with the internal network keyword:

Code snippet
"custom/wifi": {
    "exec": "$HOME/.config/waybar/get_wifi.sh",
    "interval": 5,
    "return-type": "json",
    "format": "{}"
}
(And make sure to change "custom/network" to "custom/wifi" in your modules-right list at the top of the JSON).

Use this exact CSS block in style.css:

CSS
#custom-wifi {
    background-color: #282828;
    color: #ebdbb2;
    padding: 0 10px;
    margin: 0 4px;
    border-radius: 8px;
}
Why this is the "Secret"
Waybar has a hardcoded internal module called network. When you name your custom module custom/network, the CSS engine sometimes gets "ID collisions" where it can't decide if it's styling the built-in network module or your custom script. By renaming the instance to wifi, you create a clean, unique CSS ID (#custom-wifi) that has no internal competition.

If you swap "custom/network" to "custom/wifi" in both the modules-right list and the definition block, and use #custom-wifi in the CSS, it will work.

